# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: molecular-dynamics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:molecular-dynamics/berendsen-thermostat] The **Berendsen thermostat** is an algorithm to re-scale the velocities of particles in molecular dynamics simulations to control the simulation temperature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/berendsen-thermostat] In this scheme, the system is weakly coupled to a heat bath with some temperature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/berendsen-thermostat] The thermostat suppresses fluctuations of the kinetic energy of the system and therefore cannot produce trajectories consistent with the canonical ensemble.
[src:molecular-dynamics/berendsen-thermostat] The temperature of the system is corrected such that the deviation exponentially decays with some time constant $\tau$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/berendsen-thermostat] Though the thermostat does not generate a correct canonical ensemble (especially for small systems), for large systems on the order of hundreds or thousands of atoms/molecules, the approximation yields roughly correct results for most calculated properties.
[src:molecular-dynamics/berendsen-thermostat] The scheme is widely used due to the efficiency with which it relaxes a system to some target (bath) temperature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/berendsen-thermostat] In many instances, systems are initially equilibrated using the Berendsen scheme, while properties are calculated using the widely known Nosé–Hoover thermostat, which correctly generates trajectories consistent with a canonical ensemble.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Liouville's theorem states that, for a Hamiltonian system, the local density of microstates following a particle path through phase space is constant as viewed by an observer moving with the ensemble—i.e., the convective time derivative is zero.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Thus, if the microstates are uniformly distributed in phase space initially, they shall remain so at all times.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] But Liouville's theorem does *not* imply that the ergodic hypothesis holds for all Hamiltonian systems.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] The ergodic hypothesis is often assumed in the statistical analysis of computational physics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] The analyst would assume that the average of a process parameter over time and the average over the statistical ensemble are the same.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] This assumption—that it is as good to simulate a system for long as it is to make many independent realizations of the same system—is not always correct.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Assumption of the ergodic hypothesis allows proof that certain types of perpetual motion machines of the second kind are impossible.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Systems that are ergodic are said to have the property of ergodicity; a broad range of systems in geometry, physics, and probability are ergodic.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Ergodic systems are studied in ergodic theory.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] In macroscopic systems, the timescales over which a system can explore the entirety of its own phase space can be sufficiently large that the thermodynamic equilibrium state exhibits some form of **ergodicity breaking**.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] The fact that macroscopic systems often violate the literal form of the ergodic hypothesis is an example of spontaneous symmetry breaking.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] However, complex disordered systems such as a spin glass show an even more complicated form of ergodicity breaking where the properties of the thermodynamic equilibrium state seen in practice are much more difficult to predict only by symmetry arguments.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Also conventional glasses (e.g. window glasses) violate ergodicity in a complicated manner.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Models used in finance and investment assume ergodicity, explicitly or implicitly.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] The ergodic hypothesis is prevalent in modern portfolio theory, discounted cash flow (DCF) models, and aggregate indicator models that infuse macroeconomics, among others.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] The situations modeled by these theories can be useful.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] But often they are only useful during much, but not all, of any particular time period under study.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] They can therefore miss some of the largest deviations from the standard model, such as financial crises, debt crises, and systemic risk in the banking system that occur only infrequently.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Nassim Nicholas Taleb has argued that a very important part of empirical reality in finance and investment is non-ergodic.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] An even statistical distribution of probabilities, where the system returns to every possible state an infinite number of times, is simply not the case we observe in situations where "absorbing states" are reached, a state where *ruin* is seen.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] The death of an individual, or total loss of everything, or the devolution or dismemberment of a nation state and the legal regime that accompanied it, are all absorbing states.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Thus, in finance, path dependence matters.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] A path where an individual, firm, or country hits a "stop"—an **absorbing barrier** ("anything that prevents people with skin in the game from emerging from it, and to which the system will invariably tend.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Let us call these situations *ruin*, as the entity cannot emerge from the condition.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] The central problem is that if there is a possibility of ruin, cost benefit analyses are no longer possible.") shall be non-ergodic.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] All traditional models based on standard probabilistic statistics break down in these extreme situations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] This correction is necessary for the regenerative economy to work in practice.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] In the social sciences, the ergodic hypothesis corresponds to the assumption that individuals are representative of groups and vice versa that group averages can adequately characterize what might be seen in an individual.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] This appears to not be the case: group level data often give a poor indication of individual variation, as individual standard deviations (SDs) tend to be eight times more than group SDs of the same people.
[src:molecular-dynamics/ergodic-hypothesis] Subsequently a third of the individual observations fall outside a 99.9% confidence interval of group level data.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] In the context of chemistry, molecular physics, physical chemistry, and molecular modelling, a **force field** is a computational model that is used to describe the forces between atoms (or collections of atoms) within molecules or between molecules as well as in crystals.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Force fields are a variety of interatomic potentials.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] More precisely, the force field refers to the functional form and parameter sets used to calculate the potential energy of a system on the atomistic level.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Force fields are usually used in molecular dynamics or Monte Carlo simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The parameters for a chosen energy function may be derived from classical laboratory experiment data, calculations in quantum mechanics, or both.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Force fields utilize the same concept as force fields in classical physics, with the main difference being that the force field parameters in chemistry describe the energy landscape on the atomistic level.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] From a force field, the acting forces on every particle are derived as a gradient of the potential energy with respect to the particle coordinates.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A large number of different force field types exist today (e.g. for organic molecules, ions, polymers, minerals, and metals).
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Depending on the material, different functional forms are usually chosen for the force fields since different types of atomistic interactions dominate the material behavior.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] There are various criteria that can be used for categorizing force field parametrization strategies.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] An important differentiation is 'component-specific' and 'transferable'.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For a component-specific parametrization, the considered force field is developed solely for describing a single given substance (e.g. water).
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For a transferable force field, all or some parameters are designed as building blocks and become transferable/ applicable for different substances (e.g. methyl groups in alkane transferable force fields).
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] *Coarse-grained* potentials, which are often used in long-time simulations of macromolecules such as proteins, nucleic acids, and multi-component complexes, sacrifice chemical details for higher computing efficiency.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The bond and angle terms are usually modeled by quadratic energy functions that do not allow bond breaking.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A more realistic description of a covalent bond at higher stretching is provided by the more expensive Morse potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The functional form for dihedral energy is variable from one force field to another.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Additionally, "improper torsional" terms may be added to enforce the planarity of aromatic rings and other conjugated systems, and "cross-terms" that describe the coupling of different internal variables, such as angles and bond lengths.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Some force fields also include explicit terms for hydrogen bonds.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The nonbonded terms are computationally most intensive.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A popular choice is to limit interactions to pairwise energies.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The van der Waals term is usually computed with a Lennard-Jones potential or the Mie potential and the electrostatic term with Coulomb's law.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] However, both can be buffered or scaled by a constant factor to account for electronic polarizability.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A large number of force fields based on this or similar energy expressions have been proposed in the past decades for modeling different types of materials such as molecular substances, metals, glasses etc. - see below for a comprehensive list of force fields.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The term $l_{0,ij}$ is at times differently defined or taken at different thermodynamic conditions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The bond stretching constant $k_{ij}$ can be determined from the experimental infrared spectrum, Raman spectrum, or high-level quantum-mechanical calculations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The constant $k_{ij}$ determines vibrational frequencies in molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The stronger the bond is between atoms, the higher is the value of the force constant, and the higher the wavenumber (energy) in the IR/Raman spectrum.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Though the formula of Hooke's law provides a reasonable level of accuracy at bond lengths near the equilibrium distance, it is less accurate as one moves away.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] In order to model the Morse curve better, one could employ cubic and higher powers.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] However, for most practical applications these differences are negligible, and inaccuracies in predictions of bond lengths are on the order of the thousandth of an angstrom, which is also the limit of reliability for common force fields.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A Morse potential can be employed instead to enable bond breaking and higher accuracy, even though it is less efficient to compute.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For reactive force fields, bond breaking and bond orders are additionally considered.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] where $k_{i}^{\text{angle}}$ is the force constant, $\theta _{i}$ the angle between three atoms and $\theta _{0}$ the equilibrium angle.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] where $k_{i}^{\text{dihedral}}$ is the force constant, $\phi _{i}$ the dihedral angle, $\delta _{i}$ the phase and n defines the number of minima or maxima between 0 and $2\pi$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Dihedral terms admit a range of mathematical representations, as illustrated by the multiple dihedral functional forms provided in OpenMM’s standard forces.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Electrostatic interactions are represented by a Coulomb energy, which utilizes atomic charges $q_{i}$ to represent chemical bonding ranging from covalent to polar covalent and ionic bonding.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The typical formula is the Coulomb law: $E_{\text{Coulomb}}={\frac {1}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}}}{\frac {q_{i}q_{j}}{r_{ij}}},$ where $r_{ij}$ is the distance between two atoms i and j .
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The total Coulomb energy is a sum over all pairwise combinations of atoms and usually excludes 1, 2 bonded atoms, 1, 3 bonded atoms, as well as 1, 4 bonded atoms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Atomic charges can make dominant contributions to the potential energy, especially for polar molecules and ionic compounds, and are critical to simulate the geometry, interaction energy, and the reactivity.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The assignment of charges usually uses some heuristic approach, with different possible solutions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Historically the electrostatic potential (ESP) has been used to determine partial charges with the Merz-Kollman method being one of the first.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Other methods uses population based analysis schemes of wavefunctions like the Mulliken or Löwdin population analysis.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Another method to derive partial charges are charge equilibration methods like EEM, SQE or ACKS2.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The idea is to assign geometry-dependent charges by letting electronegativity differences drive charge flow between atoms until a self-consistent minimum of the electrostatic energy is reached.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Atomistic interactions in crystal systems significantly deviate from those in molecular systems, e.g. of organic molecules.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For crystal systems, particularly multi-body interactions, these interactions are important and cannot be neglected if a high accuracy of the force field is the aim.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For crystal systems with covalent bonding, bond order potentials are usually used, e.g.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For metal systems, usually embedded atom potentials are used.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Additionally, Drude model potentials have been developed, which describe a form of attachment of electrons to nuclei.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] In addition to the functional form of the potentials, a force fields consists of the parameters of these functions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Together, they specify the interactions on the atomistic level.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The parametrization, i.e. determining of the parameter values, is crucial for the accuracy and reliability of the force field.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Different parametrization procedures have been developed for the parametrization of different substances, e.g. metals, ions, and molecules.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For different material types, usually different parametrization strategies are used.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] In general, two main types can be distinguished for the parametrization, either using data/ information from the atomistic level, e.g. from quantum mechanical calculations or spectroscopic data, or using data from macroscopic properties, e.g. the hardness or compressibility of a given material.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Often a combination of these routes is used.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Hence, one way or the other, the force field parameters are always determined in an empirical way.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Nevertheless, the term 'empirical' is often used in the context of force field parameters when macroscopic material property data was used for the fitting.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Experimental data (microscopic and macroscopic) included for the fit, for example, the enthalpy of vaporization, enthalpy of sublimation, dipole moments, and various spectroscopic properties such as vibrational frequencies.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Often, for molecular systems, quantum mechanical calculations in the gas phase are used for parametrizing intramolecular interactions and parametrizing intermolecular dispersive interactions by using macroscopic properties such as liquid densities.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The assignment of atomic charges often follows quantum mechanical protocols with some heuristics, which can lead to significant deviation in representing specific properties.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A large number of workflows and parametrization procedures have been employed in the past decades using different data and optimization strategies for determining the force field parameters.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] They differ significantly, which is also due to different focuses of different developments.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The parameters for molecular simulations of biological macromolecules such as proteins, DNA, and RNA were often derived/transferred from observations for small organic molecules, which are more accessible for experimental studies and quantum calculations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Atom types are defined for different elements as well as for the same elements in sufficiently different chemical environments.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For example, oxygen atoms in water and an oxygen atoms in a carbonyl functional group are classified as different force field types.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Typical molecular force field parameter sets include values for atomic mass, atomic charge, Lennard-Jones parameters for every atom type, as well as equilibrium values of bond lengths, bond angles, and dihedral angles.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The bonded terms refer to pairs, triplets, and quadruplets of bonded atoms, and include values for the effective spring constant for each potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Efforts to provide open source codes and methods include openMM and openMD.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The use of semi-automation or full automation, without input from chemical knowledge, is likely to increase inconsistencies at the level of atomic charges, for the assignment of remaining parameters, and likely to dilute the interpretability and performance of parameters.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A open-source software to derive parameters for different potential function is the Alexandria Chemistry Toolkit (ACT) which was published in 2025.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] It can generate and optimize physics-based force fields from scratch by machine learning.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Atom and bond parameters are considered genes of a genome, where force field accuracy is tied to the fitness of the genome.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Using a genetic algorithm (GA) and a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm, it can perform chromosomal crossovers and induce point mutations for global and local improvements closely resembling actual evolutionary operators.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Force field parameters are trained on quantum chemical energies, such as Symmetry-Adapted perturbation theory (SAPT) for non-covalent dimer interaction energies and Second-Order Møller-Plesset Perturbation Theory (MP2) scans for intramolecular energies.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A large number of force fields has been published in the past decades - mostly in scientific publications.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] In recent years, some databases have attempted to collect, categorize and make force fields digitally available.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Therein, different databases focus on different types of force fields.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For example, the openKim database focuses on interatomic functions describing the individual interactions between specific elements.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The TraPPE database focuses on transferable force fields of organic molecules (developed by the Siepmann group).
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The MolMod database focuses on molecular and ionic force fields (both component-specific and transferable).
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Functional forms and parameter sets have been defined by the developers of interatomic potentials and feature variable degrees of self-consistency and transferability.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] When functional forms of the potential terms vary or are mixed, the parameters from one interatomic potential function can typically not be used together with another interatomic potential function.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] In some cases, modifications can be made with minor effort, for example, between 9-6 Lennard-Jones potentials to 12-6 Lennard-Jones potentials.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Transfers from Buckingham potentials to harmonic potentials, or from Embedded Atom Models to harmonic potentials, on the contrary, would require many additional assumptions and may not be possible.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] In many cases, force fields can be straight forwardly combined.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Yet, often, additional specifications and assumptions are required.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] All interatomic potentials are based on approximations and experimental data, therefore often termed *empirical*.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The performance varies from higher accuracy than density functional theory (DFT) calculations, with access to million times larger systems and time scales, to random guesses depending on the force field.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The use of accurate representations of chemical bonding, combined with reproducible experimental data and validation, can lead to lasting interatomic potentials of high quality with much fewer parameters and assumptions in comparison to DFT-level quantum methods.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Possible limitations include atomic charges, also called point charges.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Most force fields rely on point charges to reproduce the electrostatic potential around molecules, which works less well for anisotropic charge distributions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Electronic polarization of the environment may be better included by using *polarizable force fields* or using a macroscopic dielectric constant.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] However, application of one value of dielectric constant is a coarse approximation in the highly heterogeneous environments of proteins, biological membranes, minerals, or electrolytes.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] All types of van der Waals forces are also strongly environment-dependent because these forces originate from interactions of induced and "instantaneous" dipoles (see Intermolecular force).
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The original Fritz London theory of these forces applies only in a vacuum.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A more general theory of van der Waals forces in condensed media was developed by A.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] McLachlan in 1963 and included the original London's approach as a special case.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The McLachlan theory predicts that van der Waals attractions in media are weaker than in vacuum and follow the *like dissolves like* rule, which means that different types of atoms interact more weakly than identical types of atoms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] This is in contrast to *combinatorial rules* or Slater-Kirkwood equation applied for development of the classical force fields.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The *combinatorial rules* state that the interaction energy of two dissimilar atoms (e.g., C...N) is an average of the interaction energies of corresponding identical atom pairs (i.e., C...C and N...N).
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] According to McLachlan's theory, the interactions of particles in media can even be fully repulsive, as observed for liquid helium, however, the lack of vaporization and presence of a freezing point contradicts a theory of purely repulsive interactions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Measurements of attractive forces between different materials (Hamaker constant) have been explained by Jacob Israelachvili.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] For example, "*the interaction between hydrocarbons across water is about 10% of that across vacuum*".
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Such effects are represented in molecular dynamics through pairwise interactions that are spatially more dense in the condensed phase relative to the gas phase and reproduced once the parameters for all phases are validated to reproduce chemical bonding, density, and cohesive/surface energy.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Limitations have been strongly felt in protein structure refinement.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The major underlying challenge is the huge conformation space of polymeric molecules, which grows beyond current computational feasibility when containing more than ~20 monomers.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Participants in Critical Assessment of protein Structure Prediction (CASP) did not try to refine their models to avoid "*a central embarrassment of molecular mechanics, namely that energy minimization or molecular dynamics generally leads to a model that is less like the experimental structure*".
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Force fields have been applied successfully for protein structure refinement in different X-ray crystallography and NMR spectroscopy applications, especially using program XPLOR.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] However, the refinement is driven mainly by a set of experimental constraints and the interatomic potentials serve mainly to remove interatomic hindrances.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The results of calculations were practically the same with rigid sphere potentials implemented in program DYANA (calculations from NMR data), or with programs for crystallographic refinement that use no energy functions at all.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] These shortcomings are related to interatomic potentials and to the inability to sample the conformation space of large molecules effectively.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Thereby also the development of parameters to tackle such large-scale problems requires new approaches.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] A specific problem area is homology modeling of proteins.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Meanwhile, alternative empirical scoring functions have been developed for ligand docking, protein folding, homology model refinement, computational protein design, and modeling of proteins in membranes.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] It was also argued that some protein force fields operate with energies that are irrelevant to protein folding or ligand binding.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The parameters of proteins force fields reproduce the enthalpy of sublimation, i.e., energy of evaporation of molecular crystals.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] However, protein folding and ligand binding are thermodynamically closer to crystallization, or liquid-solid transitions as these processes represent *freezing* of mobile molecules in condensed media.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Thus, free energy changes during protein folding or ligand binding are expected to represent a combination of an energy similar to heat of fusion (energy absorbed during melting of molecular crystals), a conformational entropy contribution, and solvation free energy.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The heat of fusion is significantly smaller than enthalpy of sublimation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Hence, the potentials describing protein folding or ligand binding need more consistent parameterization protocols, e.g., as described for IFF.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The depths of modified Lennard-Jones potentials derived from protein engineering data were also smaller than in typical potential parameters and followed the *like dissolves like* rule, as predicted by McLachlan theory.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Several force fields explicitly capture polarizability, where a particle's effective charge can be influenced by electrostatic interactions with its neighbors.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Core-shell models are common, which consist of a positively charged core particle, representing the polarizable atom, and a negatively charged particle attached to the core atom through a spring-like harmonic oscillator potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Recent examples include polarizable models with virtual electrons that reproduce image charges in metals and polarizable biomolecular force fields.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] The set of parameters used to model water or aqueous solutions (basically a force field for water) is called a water model.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Many water models have been proposed; some examples are TIP3P, TIP4P, SPC, flexible simple point charge water model (flexible SPC), ST2, and mW.
[src:molecular-dynamics/force-field-chemistry] Other solvents and methods of solvent representation are also applied within computational chemistry and physics; these are termed solvent models.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] In computational chemistry, molecular physics, and physical chemistry, the **Lennard-Jones potential** (also termed the **LJ potential** or **12-6 potential**; named for John Lennard-Jones) is an intermolecular pair potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Out of all the intermolecular potentials, the Lennard-Jones potential is probably the one that has been the most extensively studied.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] It is considered an archetype model for simple yet realistic intermolecular interactions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential is often used as a building block in molecular models (a.k.a. force fields) for more complex substances.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Many studies of the idealized "Lennard-Jones substance" use the potential to understand the physical nature of matter.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential is a pair potential, i.e. no three- or multi-body interactions are covered by the potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential is usually the standard choice for the development of theories for matter (especially soft-matter) as well as for the development and testing of computational methods and algorithms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Numerous intermolecular potentials have been proposed in the past for the modeling of simple soft repulsive and attractive interactions between spherically symmetric particles, i.e. the general shape shown in the Figure.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Examples for other potentials are the Morse potential, the Mie potential, the Buckingham potential and the Tang-Tönnies potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] While some of these may be more suited to modelling real fluids, the simplicity of the Lennard-Jones potential, as well as its often surprising ability to accurately capture real fluid behavior, has historically made it the pair-potential of greatest general importance.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] In 1924, the year that Lennard-Jones received his PhD from Cambridge University, he published a series of landmark papers on the pair potentials that would ultimately be named for him.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] In these papers he adjusted the parameters of the potential then using the result in a model of gas viscosity, seeking a set of values consistent with experiment.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] His initial results suggested a repulsive $n=13.5$ and an attractive $m=3$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Before Lennard-Jones, back in 1903, Gustav Mie had worked on effective field theories; Eduard Grüneisen built on Mie work for solids, showing that $n>m$ and $m>3$ is required for solids.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] As a result of this work the Lennard-Jones potential is sometimes called the Mie− Grüneisen potential in solid-state physics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] In 1930, after the discovery of quantum mechanics, Fritz London showed that theory predicts the long-range attractive force should have $m=6$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] In 1931, Lennard-Jones applied this form of the potential to describe many properties of fluids setting the stage for many subsequent studies.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Dimensionless reduced units can be defined based on the Lennard-Jones potential parameters, which is convenient for molecular simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] From a numerical point of view, the advantages of this unit system include computing values which are closer to unity, using simplified equations and being able to easily scale the results.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] This reduced units system requires the specification of the size parameter $\sigma$ and the energy parameter $\varepsilon$ of the Lennard-Jones potential and the mass of the particle m .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] All physical properties can be converted straightforwardly taking the respective dimension into account, see table.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The reduced units are often abbreviated and indicated by an asterisk.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] In general, reduced units can also be built up on other molecular interaction potentials that consist of a length parameter and an energy parameter.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] (1) and Figure on the top, has an infinite range.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Only under its consideration, the 'true' and 'full' Lennard-Jones potential is examined.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For the evaluation of an observable of an ensemble of particles interacting by the Lennard-Jones potential using molecular simulations, the interactions can only be evaluated explicitly up to a certain distance – simply due to the fact that the number of particles will always be finite.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The maximum distance applied in a simulation is usually referred to as 'cut-off' radius $r_{\mathrm {c} }$ (because the Lennard-Jones potential is radially symmetric).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] To obtain thermophysical properties (both macroscopic or microscopic) of the 'true' and 'full' Lennard-Jones (LJ) potential, the contribution of the potential beyond the cut-off radius has to be accounted for.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Different correction schemes have been developed to account for the influence of the long-range interactions in simulations and to sustain a sufficiently good approximation of the 'full' potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] They are based on simplifying assumptions regarding the structure of the fluid.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For simple cases, such as in studies of the equilibrium of homogeneous fluids, simple correction terms yield excellent results.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] In other cases, such as in studies of inhomogeneous systems with different phases, accounting for the long-range interactions is more tedious.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] These corrections are usually referred to as 'long-range corrections'.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For most properties, simple analytical expressions are known and well established.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The hypothetical true value of the observable of the Lennard-Jones potential at truly infinite cut-off distance (thermodynamic limit) $X_{\mathrm {true} }$ can in general only be estimated.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Furthermore, the quality of the long-range correction scheme depends on the cut-off radius.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The assumptions made with the correction schemes are usually not justified at (very) short cut-off radii.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] This is illustrated in the example shown in Figure on the right.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The long-range correction scheme is said to be converged, if the remaining error of the correction scheme is sufficiently small at a given cut-off distance, cf.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential – as an archetype for intermolecular potentials – has been used numerous times as starting point for the development of more elaborate or more generalized intermolecular potentials.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Various extensions and modifications of the Lennard-Jones potential have been proposed in the literature; a more extensive list is given in the 'interatomic potential' article.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The following list refers only to several example potentials that are directly related to the Lennard-Jones potential and are of both historic importance and still relevant for present research.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones truncated & shifted (LJTS) potential is an often used alternative to the 'full' Lennard-Jones potential (see Eq.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The 'full' and the 'truncated & shifted' Lennard-Jones potential have to be kept strictly separate.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] They are simply two different intermolecular potentials yielding different thermophysical properties.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Hence, the LJTS potential is truncated at $r_{\mathrm {end} }$ and shifted by the corresponding energy value $V_{\mathrm {LJ} }(r_{\mathrm {end} })$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The latter is applied to avoid a discontinuity jump of the potential at $r_{\mathrm {end} }$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For the LJTS potential, no long-range interactions beyond $r_{\mathrm {end} }$ are required – neither explicitly nor implicitly.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The most frequently used version of the Lennard-Jones truncated & shifted potential is the one with $r_{\mathrm {end} }=2.5\,\sigma$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Nevertheless, different $r_{\mathrm {end} }$ values have been used in the literature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Each LJTS potential with a given truncation radius $r_{\mathrm {end} }$ has to be considered as a potential and accordingly a substance of its own.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The LJTS potential is computationally significantly cheaper than the 'full' Lennard-Jones potential, but still covers the essential physical features of matter (the presence of a critical and a triple point, soft repulsive and attractive interactions, phase equilibria etc.).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Therefore, the LJTS potential is used for the testing of new algorithms, simulation methods, and new physical theories.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Interestingly, for homogeneous systems, the intermolecular forces that are calculated from the LJ and the LJTS potential at a given distance are the same (since ${\text{d}}V/{\text{d}}r$ is the same), whereas the potential energy and the pressure are affected by the shifting.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Also, the properties of the LJTS substance may furthermore be affected by the chosen simulation algorithm, i.e.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] MD or MC sampling (this is in general not the case for the 'full' Lennard-Jones potential).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For the LJTS potential with $r_{\mathrm {end} }=2.5\,\sigma$ , the potential energy shift is approximately 1/60 of the dispersion energy at the potential well: $V_{\mathrm {LJ} }(r_{\mathrm {end} }=2.5\,\sigma )=-0.0163\,\varepsilon$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Figure on the right shows the comparison of the vapor–liquid equilibrium of the 'full' Lennard-Jones potential and the 'Lennard-Jones truncated & shifted' potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The 'full' Lennard-Jones potential results prevail a significantly higher critical temperature and pressure compared to the LJTS potential results, but the critical density is very similar.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The vapor pressure and the enthalpy of vaporization are influenced more strongly by the long-range interactions than the saturated densities.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] This is due to the fact that the potential is manipulated mainly energetically by the truncation and shifting.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential is not only of fundamental importance in computational chemistry and soft-matter physics, but also for the modeling of real substances.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential is used for fundamental studies on the behavior of matter and for elucidating atomistic phenomena.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] It is also often used for somewhat special use cases, e.g. for studying thermophysical properties of two- or four-dimensional substances (instead of the classical three spatial directions of our universe).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] There are two main applications of the Lennard-Jones potentials: (i) for studying the hypothetical Lennard-Jones substance and (ii) for modeling interactions in real substance models.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] These two applications are discussed in the following.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] A Lennard-Jones substance or "Lennard-Jonesium" is the name given to an idealized substance which would result from atoms or molecules interacting exclusively through the Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Statistical mechanics and computer simulations can be used to study the Lennard-Jones potential and to obtain thermophysical properties of the 'Lennard-Jones substance'.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones substance is often referred to as 'Lennard-Jonesium,' suggesting that it is viewed as a (fictive) chemical element.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Moreover, its energy and length parameters can be adjusted to fit many different real substances.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Both the Lennard-Jones potential and, accordingly, the Lennard-Jones substance are simplified yet realistic models, such as they accurately capture essential physical principles like the presence of a critical and a triple point, condensation and freezing.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Due in part to its mathematical simplicity, the Lennard-Jones potential has been extensively used in studies on matter since the early days of computer simulation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Thermophysical properties of the Lennard-Jones substance, i.e. particles interacting with the Lennard-Jones potential can be obtained using statistical mechanics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Some properties can be computed analytically, i.e. with machine precision, whereas most properties can only be obtained by performing molecular simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The latter will in general be superimposed by both statistical and systematic uncertainties.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The virial coefficients can for example be computed directly from the Lennard-potential using algebraic expressions and reported data has therefore no uncertainty.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Molecular simulation results, e.g. the pressure at a given temperature and density has both statistical and systematic uncertainties.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Molecular simulations of the Lennard-Jones potential can in general be performed using either molecular dynamics (MD) simulations or Monte Carlo (MC) simulation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For MC simulations, the Lennard-Jones potential $V_{\mathrm {LJ} }(r)$ is directly used, whereas MD simulations are always based on the derivative of the potential, i.e. the force $F=-\mathrm {d} V/\mathrm {d} r$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] These differences in combination with differences in the treatment of the long-range interactions (see below) can influence computed thermophysical properties.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Since the *Lennard-Jonesium* is the archetype for the modeling of simple yet realistic intermolecular interactions, a large number of thermophysical properties were studied and reported in the literature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Computer experiment data of the Lennard-Jones potential is presently considered the most accurately known data in classical mechanics computational chemistry.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Hence, such data is also mostly used as a benchmark for validating and testing new algorithms and theories.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential has been constantly used since the early days of molecular simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The first results from computer experiments for the Lennard-Jones potential were reported by Rosenbluth and Rosenbluth and Wood and Parker after molecular simulations on "fast computing machines" became available in 1953.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Since then many studies reported data of the Lennard-Jones substance; approximately 50,000 data points are publicly available.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The current state of research on the thermophysical properties of the Lennard-Jones substance is summarized by Stephan et al.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] (which did not cover transport and mixture properties).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) provides examples of molecular dynamics and Monte Carlo codes along with results obtained from them.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Transport property data of Lennard-Jones fluids have been compiled by Bell et al. and Lautenschaeger and Hasse.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Figure on the right shows the phase diagram of the Lennard-Jones fluid.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Phase equilibria of the Lennard-Jones potential have been studied numerous times and are accordingly known today with good precision.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Figure shows results correlations derived from computer experiment results (hence, lines instead of data points are shown).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The mean intermolecular interaction of a Lennard-Jones particle strongly depends on the thermodynamic state, i.e., temperature and pressure (or density).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For solid states, the attractive Lennard-Jones interaction plays a dominant role – especially at low temperatures.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For liquid states, no ordered structure is present compared to solid states.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The mean potential energy per particle is negative.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For gaseous states, attractive interactions of the Lennard-Jones potential play a minor role – since they are far distanced.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The main part of the internal energy is stored as kinetic energy for gaseous states.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] At supercritical states, the attractive Lennard-Jones interaction plays a minor role.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] With increasing temperature, the mean kinetic energy of the particles increases and exceeds the energy well of the Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Hence, the particles mainly interact by the potentials' soft repulsive interactions and the mean potential energy per particle is accordingly positive.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Overall, due to the large timespan the Lennard-Jones potential has been studied and thermophysical property data has been reported in the literature and computational resources were insufficient for accurate simulations (to modern standards), a noticeable amount of data is known to be dubious.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Nevertheless, in many studies such data is used as reference.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The lack of data repositories and data assessment is a crucial element for future work in the long-going field of Lennard-Jones potential research.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The most important characteristic points of the Lennard-Jones potential are the critical point and the vapor–liquid–solid triple point.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] They were studied numerous times in the literature and compiled in Ref.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The given uncertainties were calculated from the standard deviation of the critical parameters derived from the most reliable available vapor–liquid equilibrium data sets.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] These uncertainties can be assumed as a lower limit to the accuracy with which the critical point of fluid can be obtained from molecular simulation results.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The uncertainties represent the scattering of data from different authors.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The critical point of the Lennard-Jones substance has been studied far more often than the triple point.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For both the critical point and the vapor–liquid–solid triple point, several studies reported results out of the above stated ranges.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The above stated data is the presently assumed correct and reliable data.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Nevertheless, the determinateness of the critical temperature and the triple point temperature is still unsatisfactory.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Evidently, the phase coexistence curves (cf. figures) are of fundamental importance to characterize the Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Furthermore, *Brown's characteristic curves* yield an illustrative description of essential features of the Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Brown's characteristic curves are defined as curves on which a certain thermodynamic property of the substance matches that of an ideal gas.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For a real fluid, Z and its derivatives can match the values of the ideal gas for special T , $\rho$ combinations only as a result of Gibbs' phase rule.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The resulting points collectively constitute a characteristic curve.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Four main characteristic curves are defined: One 0th-order (named *Zeno curve*) and three 1st-order curves (named *Amagat*, *Boyle*, and *Charles curve*).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The characteristic curve are required to have a negative or zero curvature throughout and a single maximum in a double-logarithmic pressure-temperature diagram.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Furthermore, Brown's characteristic curves and the virial coefficients are directly linked in the limit of the ideal gas and are therefore known exactly at $\rho \rightarrow 0$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Both computer simulation results and equation of state results have been reported in the literature for the Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Points on the Zeno curve Z have a compressibility factor of unity $Z=p/(\rho T)=1$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Zeno curve originates at the Boyle temperature $T_{\mathrm {B} }=3.417927982\,\varepsilon k_{\mathrm {B} }^{-1}$ , surrounds the critical point, and has a slope of unity in the low temperature limit.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Boyle curve originates with the Zeno curve at the Boyle temperature, faintly surrounds the critical point, and ends on the vapor pressure curve.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Joule-Thomson inversion curve) have $\left.{\frac {\mathrm {d} Z}{\mathrm {d} T}}\right|_{p}=0$ and more importantly $\left.{\frac {\mathrm {d} T}{\mathrm {d} p}}\right|_{h}=0$ , i.e. no temperature change upon isenthalpic throttling.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] It originates at $T=6.430798418\,\varepsilon k_{\mathrm {B} }^{-1}$ in the ideal gas limit, crosses the Zeno curve, and terminates on the vapor pressure curve.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Points on the Amagat curve A have $\left.{\frac {\mathrm {d} Z}{\mathrm {d} T}}\right|_{\rho }=0$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] It also starts in the ideal gas limit at $T=25.15242837\,\varepsilon k_{\mathrm {B} }^{-1}$ , surrounds the critical point and the other three characteristic curves and passes into the solid phase region.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] A comprehensive discussion of the characteristic curves of the Lennard-Jones potential is given by Stephan and Deiters.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Properties of the Lennard-Jones fluid have been studied extensively in the literature due to the outstanding importance of the Lennard-Jones potential in soft-matter physics and related fields.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] About 50 datasets of computer experiment data for the vapor–liquid equilibrium have been published to date.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Furthermore, more than 35,000 data points at homogeneous fluid states have been published over the years and recently been compiled and assessed for outliers in an open access database.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] This status quo can not be considered satisfactory considering the fact that statistical uncertainties usually reported for single data sets are significantly below the above stated values (even for far more complex molecular force fields).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Both phase equilibrium properties and homogeneous state properties at arbitrary density can in general only be obtained from molecular simulations, whereas virial coefficients can be computed directly from the Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Numerical data for the second and third virial coefficient is available in a wide temperature range.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For higher virial coefficients (up to the sixteenth), the number of available data points decreases with increasing number of the virial coefficient.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Also transport properties (viscosity, heat conductivity, and self diffusion coefficient) of the Lennard-Jones fluid have been studied, but the database is significantly less dense than for homogeneous equilibrium properties like $pvT$ – or internal energy data.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Moreover, a large number of analytical models (equations of state) have been developed for the description of the Lennard-Jones fluid (see below for details).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The database and knowledge for the Lennard-Jones solid is significantly poorer than for the fluid phases.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] It was realized early that the interactions in solid phases should not be approximated to be pair-wise additive – especially for metals.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Nevertheless, the Lennard-Jones potential is used in solid-state physics due to its simplicity and computational efficiency.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Hence, the basic properties of the solid phases and the solid–fluid phase equilibria have been investigated several times, e.g.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones substance form fcc (face centered cubic), hcp (hexagonal close-packed) and other close-packed polytype lattices – depending on temperature and pressure, cf. figure above with phase diagram.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] At low temperature and up to moderate pressure, the hcp lattice is energetically favored and therefore the equilibrium structure.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The fcc lattice structure is energetically favored at both high temperature and high pressure and therefore overall the equilibrium structure in a wider state range.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Hence, only the fcc solid phase exhibits phase equilibria with the liquid and supercritical phase, cf. figure above with phase diagram.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Note, that other and significantly differing values have also been reported in the literature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Hence, the database for the fcc-hcp–vapor triple point should be further solidified in the future.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Mixtures of Lennard-Jones particles are mostly used as a prototype for the development of theories and methods of solutions, but also to study properties of solutions in general.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] This dates back to the fundamental work of conformal solution theory of Longuet-Higgins and Leland and Rowlinson and co-workers.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Those are today the basis of most theories for mixtures.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Mixtures of two or more Lennard-Jones components are set up by changing at least one potential interaction parameter ( $\varepsilon$ or $\sigma$ ) of one of the components with respect to the other.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For a binary mixture, this yields three types of pair interactions that are all modeled by the Lennard-Jones potential: 1-1, 2-2, and 1-2 interactions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For the cross interactions 1–2, additional assumptions are required for the specification of parameters $\varepsilon _{\mathrm {12} }$ or $\sigma _{\mathrm {12} }$ from $\varepsilon _{\mathrm {11} }$ , $\sigma _{\mathrm {11} }$ and $\varepsilon _{\mathrm {22} }$ , $\sigma _{\mathrm {22} }$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Various choices (all more or less empirical and not rigorously based on physical arguments) can be used for these so-called combination rules.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The parameter $\xi _{12}$ is an additional state-independent interaction parameter for the mixture.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The parameter $\eta _{12}$ is usually set to unity since the arithmetic mean can be considered physically plausible for the cross-interaction size parameter.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The parameter $\xi _{12}$ on the other hand is often used to adjust the geometric mean so as to reproduce the phase behavior of the model mixture.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For analytical models, e.g. equations of state, the deviation parameter is usually written as $k_{12}=1-\xi _{12}$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For $\xi _{12}>1$ , the cross-interaction dispersion energy and accordingly the attractive force between unlike particles is intensified, and the attractive forces between unlike particles are diminished for $\xi _{12}<1$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For Lennard-Jones mixtures, both fluid and solid phase equilibria can be studied, i.e. vapor–liquid, liquid–liquid, gas–gas, solid–vapor, solid–liquid, and solid–solid.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Accordingly, different types of triple points (three-phase equilibria) and critical points can exist as well as different eutectic and azeotropic points.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Binary Lennard-Jones mixtures in the fluid region (various types of equilibria of liquid and gas phases) have been studied more comprehensively than phase equilibria comprising solid phases.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] A large number of different Lennard-Jones mixtures have been studied in the literature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] To date, no standard for such has been established.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Usually, the binary interaction parameters and the two component parameters are chosen such that a mixture with properties convenient for a given task are obtained.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Yet, this often makes comparisons tricky.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For the fluid phase behavior, mixtures exhibit practically ideal behavior (in the sense of Raoult's law) for $\xi _{12}=1$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For $\xi _{12}>1$ attractive interactions prevail and the mixtures tend to form high-boiling azeotropes, i.e. a lower pressure than pure components' vapor pressures is required to stabilize the vapor–liquid equilibrium.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For $\xi _{12}<1$ repulsive interactions prevail and mixtures tend to form low-boiling azeotropes, i.e. a higher pressure than pure components' vapor pressures is required to stabilize the vapor–liquid equilibrium since the mean dispersive forces are decreased.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Particularly low values of $\xi _{12}$ furthermore will result in liquid–liquid miscibility gaps.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Also various types of phase equilibria comprising solid phases have been studied in the literature, e.g. by Carol and co-workers.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Also, cases exist where the solid phase boundaries interrupt fluid phase equilibria.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] However, for phase equilibria that comprise solid phases, the amount of published data is sparse.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] A large number of equations of state (EOS) for the Lennard-Jones potential/ substance have been proposed since its characterization and evaluation became available with the first computer simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Due to the fundamental importance of the Lennard-Jones potential, most currently available molecular-based EOS are built around the Lennard-Jones fluid.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] They have been comprehensively reviewed by Stephan et al.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Equations of state for the Lennard-Jones fluid are of particular importance in soft-matter physics and physical chemistry, used as starting point for the development of EOS for complex fluids, e.g. polymers and associating fluids.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The monomer units of these models are usually directly adapted from Lennard-Jones EOS as a building block, e.g. the PHC EOS, the BACKONE EOS, and SAFT type EOS.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] More than 30 Lennard-Jones EOS have been proposed in the literature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] A comprehensive evaluation of such EOS showed that several EOS describe the Lennard-Jones potential with good and similar accuracy, but none of them is outstanding.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Three of those EOS show an unacceptable unphysical behavior in some fluid region, e.g. multiple van der Waals loops, while being elsewise reasonably precise.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Only the Lennard-Jones EOS of Kolafa and Nezbeda was found to be robust and precise for most thermodynamic properties of the Lennard-Jones fluid.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Furthermore, the Lennard-Jones EOS of Johnson et al. was found to be less precise for practically all available reference data than the Kolafa and Nezbeda EOS.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential is extensively used for molecular modeling of real substances.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] There are essentially two ways the Lennard-Jones potential can be used for molecular modeling: (1) A real substance atom or molecule is modeled directly by the Lennard-Jones potential, which yields very good results for noble gases and methane, i.e. dispersively interacting spherical particles.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] In the case of methane, the molecule is assumed to be spherically symmetric and the hydrogen atoms are fused with the carbon atom to a common unit.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] This simplification can in general also be applied to more complex molecules, but yields usually poor results.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] (2) A real substance molecule is built of multiple Lennard-Jones interactions sites, which can be connected either by rigid bonds or flexible additional potentials (and eventually also consists of other potential types, e.g. partial charges).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Molecular models (often referred to as 'force fields') for practically all molecular and ionic particles can be constructed using this scheme for example for alkanes.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Upon using the first outlined approach, the molecular model has only the two parameters of the Lennard-Jones potential $\varepsilon$ and $\sigma$ that can be used for the fitting, e.g. $\varepsilon /k_{\mathrm {B} }=120\,\mathrm {K}$ and $\sigma =0.34\,\mathrm {nm}$ can be used for argon.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Upon adjusting the model parameters ε and σ to real substance properties, the Lennard-Jones potential can be used to describe simple substance (like noble gases) with good accuracy.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Evidently, this approach is only a good approximation for spherical and simply dispersively interacting molecules and atoms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The direct use of the Lennard-Jones potential has the great advantage that simulation results and theories for the Lennard-Jones potential can be used directly.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Hence, available results for the Lennard-Jones potential and substance can be directly scaled using the appropriate $\varepsilon$ and $\sigma$ (see reduced units).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential parameters $\varepsilon$ and $\sigma$ can in general be fitted to any desired real substance property.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] In soft-matter physics, usually experimental data for the vapor–liquid phase equilibrium or the critical point are used for the parametrization; in solid-state physics, rather the compressibility, heat capacity or lattice constants are employed.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The second outlined approach of using the Lennard-Jones potential as a building block of elongated and complex molecules is far more sophisticated.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Molecular models are thereby tailor-made in a sense that simulation results are only applicable for that particular model.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] This development approach for molecular force fields is today mainly performed in soft-matter physics and associated fields such as chemical engineering, chemistry, and computational biology.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] A large number of force fields are based on the Lennard-Jones potential, e.g. the TraPPE force field, the OPLS force field, and the MolMod force field (an overview of molecular force fields is out of the scope of the present article).
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] For the state-of-the-art modeling of solid-state materials, more elaborate multi-body potentials (e.g.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential gives a good description of molecular interactions in fluid phases, whereas molecular interactions in solid phases are only roughly well described.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] This is mainly due to the fact that multi-body interactions play a significant role in solid phases, which are not comprised in the Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Therefore, the Lennard-Jones potential is extensively used in soft-matter physics and associated fields, whereas it is less frequently used in solid-state physics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Due to its simplicity, the Lennard-Jones potential is often used to describe the properties of gases and simple fluids and to model dispersive and repulsive interactions in molecular models.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] It is especially accurate for noble gas atoms and methane.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] It is furthermore a good approximation for molecular interactions at long and short distances for neutral atoms and molecules.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Therefore, the Lennard-Jones potential is very often used as a building block of molecular models of complex molecules, e.g. alkanes or water.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] The Lennard-Jones potential can also be used to model the adsorption interactions at solid–fluid interfaces, i.e. physisorption or chemisorption.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] It is well accepted, that the main limitations of the Lennard-Jones potential lie in the fact the potential is a pair potential (does not cover multi-body interactions) and that the $1/r^{12}$ exponent term is used for the repulsion.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Results from quantum chemistry suggest that a higher exponent than 12 has to be used, i.e. a steeper potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/lennard-jones-potential] Furthermore, the Lennard-Jones potential has a limited flexibility, i.e. only the two model parameters $\varepsilon$ and $\sigma$ can be used for the fitting to describe a real substance.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Because molecular systems typically consist of a vast number of particles, it is impossible to determine the properties of such complex systems analytically; MD simulation circumvents this problem by using numerical methods.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] However, long MD simulations are mathematically ill-conditioned, generating cumulative errors in numerical integration that can be minimized with proper selection of algorithms and parameters, but not eliminated.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For systems that obey the ergodic hypothesis, the evolution of one molecular dynamics simulation may be used to determine the macroscopic thermodynamic properties of the system: the time averages of an ergodic system correspond to microcanonical ensemble averages.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] MD has also been termed "statistical mechanics by numbers" and "Laplace's vision of Newtonian mechanics" of predicting the future by animating nature's forces and allowing insight into molecular motion on an atomic scale.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Interest in the time evolution of N-body systems dates much earlier to the seventeenth century, beginning with Isaac Newton, and continued into the following century largely with a focus on celestial mechanics and issues such as the stability of the Solar System.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Many of the numerical methods used today were developed during this time period, which predates the use of computers; for example, the most common integration algorithm used today, the Verlet integration algorithm, was used as early as 1791 by Jean Baptiste Joseph Delambre.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Numerical calculations with these algorithms can be considered to be MD done "by hand".
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] As early as 1941, integration of the many-body equations of motion was carried out with analog computers.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Some undertook the labor-intensive work of modeling atomic motion by constructing physical models, e.g., using macroscopic spheres.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The aim was to arrange them in such a way as to replicate the structure of a liquid and use this to examine its behavior.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Following the discovery of microscopic particles and the development of computers, interest expanded beyond the proving ground of gravitational systems to the statistical properties of matter.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Today, this seminal work is known as the Fermi–Pasta–Ulam–Tsingou problem.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The time evolution of the energy from the original work is shown in the figure to the right.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In 1957, Berni Alder and Thomas Wainwright used an IBM 704 computer to simulate perfectly elastic collisions between hard spheres.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In 1960, in perhaps the first realistic simulation of matter, J.B.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Gibson *et al*. simulated radiation damage of solid copper by using a Born–Mayer type of repulsive interaction along with a cohesive surface force.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In 1964, Aneesur Rahman published simulations of liquid argon that used a Lennard-Jones potential; calculations of system properties, such as the coefficient of self-diffusion, compared well with experimental data.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Today, the Lennard-Jones potential is still one of the most frequently used intermolecular potentials.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] It is used for describing simple substances (a.k.a.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Lennard-Jonesium) for conceptual and model studies and as a building block in many force fields of real substances.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] First used in theoretical physics, the molecular dynamics method gained popularity in materials science soon afterward, and since the 1970s it has also been commonly used in biochemistry and biophysics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] MD is frequently used to refine 3-dimensional structures of proteins and other macromolecules based on experimental constraints from X-ray crystallography or NMR spectroscopy.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In physics, MD is used to examine the dynamics of atomic-level phenomena that cannot be observed directly, such as thin film growth and ion subplantation, and to examine the physical properties of nanotechnological devices that have not or cannot yet be created.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In principle, MD can be used for *ab initio* prediction of protein structure by simulating folding of the polypeptide chain from a random coil.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] MD can also be used to compute other thermodynamic properties such as drug solubilities and free energies of solvation including in polymers.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The results of MD simulations can be tested through comparison to experiments that measure molecular dynamics, of which a popular method is NMR spectroscopy.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] MD-derived structure predictions can be tested through community-wide experiments in Critical Assessment of Protein Structure Prediction (CASP), although the method has historically had limited success in this area.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] MD simulation has been reported for pharmacophore development and drug design.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For example, Pinto *et al*. implemented MD simulations of Bcl-xL complexes to calculate average positions of critical amino acids involved in ligand binding.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Carlson *et al*. implemented molecular dynamics simulations to identify compounds that complement a receptor while causing minimal disruption to the conformation and flexibility of the active site.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Snapshots of the protein at constant time intervals during the simulation were overlaid to identify conserved binding regions (conserved in at least three out of eleven frames) for pharmacophore development.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Spyrakis *et al*. relied on a workflow of MD simulations, fingerprints for ligands and proteins (FLAP) and linear discriminant analysis (LDA) to identify the best ligand-protein conformations to act as pharmacophore templates based on retrospective ROC analysis of the resulting pharmacophores.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Critical contacts can then be converted into pharmacophore models that can be used for virtual screening.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] An important factor is intramolecular hydrogen bonds, which are not explicitly included in modern force fields, but described as Coulomb interactions of atomic point charges.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This is a crude approximation because hydrogen bonds have a partially quantum mechanical and chemical nature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Furthermore, electrostatic interactions are usually calculated using the dielectric constant of a vacuum, even though the surrounding aqueous solution has a much higher dielectric constant.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Thus, using the macroscopic dielectric constant at short interatomic distances is questionable.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Finally, van der Waals interactions in MD are usually described by Lennard-Jones potentials based on the Fritz London theory that is only applicable in a vacuum.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] However, all types of van der Waals forces are ultimately of electrostatic origin and therefore depend on dielectric properties of the environment.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The direct measurement of attraction forces between different materials (as Hamaker constant) shows that "the interaction between hydrocarbons across water is about 10% of that across vacuum".
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The environment-dependence of van der Waals forces is neglected in standard simulations, but can be included by developing polarizable force fields.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The design of a molecular dynamics simulation should account for the available computational power.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Simulation size (*n* = number of particles), timestep, and total time duration must be selected so that the calculation can finish within a reasonable time period.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] However, the simulations should be long enough to be relevant to the time scales of the natural processes being studied.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] To make statistically valid conclusions from the simulations, the time span simulated should match the kinetics of the natural process.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Otherwise, it is analogous to making conclusions about how a human walks when only looking at less than one footstep.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Most scientific publications about the dynamics of proteins and DNA use data from simulations spanning nanoseconds (10−9 s) to microseconds (10−6 s).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] To obtain these simulations, several CPU-days to CPU-years are needed.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Parallel algorithms allow the load to be distributed among CPUs; an example is the spatial or force decomposition algorithm.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] During a classical MD simulation, the most CPU intensive task is the evaluation of the potential as a function of the particles' internal coordinates.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Within that energy evaluation, the most expensive one is the non-bonded or non-covalent part.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In big O notation, common molecular dynamics simulations scale by $O(n^{2})$ if all pair-wise electrostatic and van der Waals interactions must be accounted for explicitly.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This computational cost can be reduced by employing electrostatics methods such as particle mesh Ewald summation ( $O(n\log(n))$ ), particle-particle-particle mesh (P3M), or good spherical cutoff methods ( $O(n)$ ).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Another factor that impacts total CPU time needed by a simulation is the size of the integration timestep.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This is the time length between evaluations of the potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The timestep must be chosen small enough to avoid discretization errors (i.e., smaller than the period related to fastest vibrational frequency in the system).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Typical timesteps for classical MD are on the order of 1 femtosecond (10−15 s).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This value may be extended by using algorithms such as the SHAKE constraint algorithm, which fix the vibrations of the fastest atoms (e.g., hydrogens) into place.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Multiple time scale methods have also been developed, which allow extended times between updates of slower long-range forces.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For simulating molecules in a solvent, a choice should be made between an explicit and implicit solvent.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Explicit solvent particles (such as the TIP3P, SPC/E and SPC-f water models) must be calculated expensively by the force field, while implicit solvents use a mean-field approach.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Using an explicit solvent is computationally expensive, requiring inclusion of roughly ten times more particles in the simulation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] But the granularity and viscosity of explicit solvent is essential to reproduce certain properties of the solute molecules.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This is especially important to reproduce chemical kinetics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In all kinds of molecular dynamics simulations, the simulation box size must be large enough to avoid boundary condition artifacts.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Boundary conditions are often treated by choosing fixed values at the edges (which may cause artifacts), or by employing periodic boundary conditions in which one side of the simulation loops back to the opposite side, mimicking a bulk phase (which may cause artifacts too).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In the microcanonical ensemble, the system is isolated from changes in moles (N), volume (V), and energy (E).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] It corresponds to an adiabatic process with no heat exchange.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A microcanonical molecular dynamics trajectory may be seen as an exchange of potential and kinetic energy, with total energy being conserved.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The potential energy function $U(X)$ of the system is a function of the particle coordinates X .
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] It is referred to simply as the *potential* in physics, or the *force field* in chemistry.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The first equation comes from Newton's laws of motion; the force F acting on each particle in the system can be calculated as the negative gradient of $U(X)$ .
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For every time step, each particle's position X and velocity V may be integrated with a symplectic integrator method such as Verlet integration.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The time evolution of X and V is called a trajectory.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Given the initial positions (e.g., from theoretical knowledge) and velocities (e.g., randomized Gaussian), we can calculate all future (or past) positions and velocities.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] One frequent source of confusion is the meaning of temperature in MD.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Commonly we have experience with macroscopic temperatures, which involve a huge number of particles, but temperature is a statistical quantity.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] If there is a large enough number of atoms, statistical temperature can be estimated from the *instantaneous temperature*, which is found by equating the kinetic energy of the system to *nkBT*/2, where *n* is the number of degrees of freedom of the system.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A temperature-related phenomenon arises due to the small number of atoms that are used in MD simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For example, consider simulating the growth of a copper film starting with a substrate containing 500 atoms and a deposition energy of 100 eV.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In the real world, the 100 eV from the deposited atom would rapidly be transported through and shared among a large number of atoms ( $10^{10}$ or more) with no big change in temperature.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] When there are only 500 atoms, however, the substrate is almost immediately vaporized by the deposition.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Something similar happens in biophysical simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The temperature of the system in NVE is naturally raised when macromolecules such as proteins undergo exothermic conformational changes and binding.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In the canonical ensemble, amount of substance (N), volume (V) and temperature (T) are conserved.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] It is also sometimes called constant temperature molecular dynamics (CTMD).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In NVT, the energy of endothermic and exothermic processes is exchanged with a thermostat.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A variety of thermostat algorithms are available to add and remove energy from the boundaries of an MD simulation in a more or less realistic way, approximating the canonical ensemble.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Popular methods to control temperature include velocity rescaling, the Nosé–Hoover thermostat, Nosé–Hoover chains, the Berendsen thermostat, the Andersen thermostat and Langevin dynamics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The Berendsen thermostat might introduce the flying ice cube effect, which leads to unphysical translations and rotations of the simulated system.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] It is not trivial to obtain a canonical ensemble distribution of conformations and velocities using these algorithms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] How this depends on system size, thermostat choice, thermostat parameters, time step and integrator is the subject of many articles in the field.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In the isothermal–isobaric ensemble, amount of substance (N), pressure (P) and temperature (T) are conserved.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In addition to a thermostat, a barostat is needed.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] It corresponds most closely to laboratory conditions with a flask open to ambient temperature and pressure.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In the simulation of biological membranes, isotropic pressure control is not appropriate.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For lipid bilayers, pressure control occurs under constant membrane area (NPAT) or constant surface tension "gamma" (NPγT).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The replica exchange method is a generalized ensemble.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] It was originally created to deal with the slow dynamics of disordered spin systems.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The replica exchange MD (REMD) formulation tries to overcome the multiple-minima problem by exchanging the temperature of non-interacting replicas of the system running at several temperatures.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A molecular dynamics simulation requires the definition of a potential function, or a description of the terms by which the particles in the simulation will interact.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In chemistry and biology this is usually referred to as a force field and in materials physics as an interatomic potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The reduction from a fully quantum description to a classical potential entails two main approximations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The first one is the Born–Oppenheimer approximation, which states that the dynamics of electrons are so fast that they can be considered to react instantaneously to the motion of their nuclei.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] As a consequence, they may be treated separately.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The second one treats the nuclei, which are much heavier than electrons, as point particles that follow classical Newtonian dynamics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In classical molecular dynamics, the effect of the electrons is approximated as one potential energy surface, usually representing the ground state.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Empirical potentials used in chemistry are frequently called force fields, while those used in materials physics are called interatomic potentials.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Most force fields in chemistry are empirical and consist of a summation of bonded forces associated with chemical bonds, bond angles, and bond dihedrals, and non-bonded forces associated with van der Waals forces and electrostatic charge.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Empirical potentials represent quantum-mechanical effects in a limited way through ad hoc functional approximations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Because of the non-local nature of non-bonded interactions, they involve at least weak interactions between all particles in the system.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Its calculation is normally the bottleneck in the speed of MD simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] To lower the computational cost, force fields employ numerical approximations such as shifted cutoff radii, reaction field algorithms, particle mesh Ewald summation, or the newer particle–particle-particle–mesh (P3M).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Chemistry force fields commonly employ preset bonding arrangements (an exception being *ab initio* dynamics), and thus are unable to model the process of chemical bond breaking and reactions explicitly.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] On the other hand, many of the potentials used in physics, such as those based on the bond order formalism can describe several different coordinations of a system and bond breaking.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Examples of such potentials include the Brenner potential for hydrocarbons and its further developments for the C-Si-H and C-O-H systems.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The ReaxFF potential can be considered a fully reactive hybrid between bond order potentials and chemistry force fields.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The potential functions representing the non-bonded energy are formulated as a sum over interactions between the particles of the system.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The simplest choice, employed in many popular force fields, is the "pair potential", in which the total potential energy can be calculated from the sum of energy contributions between pairs of atoms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Therefore, these force fields are also called "additive force fields".
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] An example of such a pair potential is the non-bonded Lennard-Jones potential (also termed the 6–12 potential), used for calculating van der Waals forces.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Another example is the Born (ionic) model of the ionic lattice.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The first term in the next equation is Coulomb's law for a pair of ions, the second term is the short-range repulsion explained by Pauli's exclusion principle and the final term is the dispersion interaction term.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Usually, a simulation only includes the dipolar term, although sometimes the quadrupolar term is also included.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] When *nl* = 6, this potential is also called the Coulomb–Buckingham potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In many-body potentials, the potential energy includes the effects of three or more particles interacting with each other.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In simulations with pairwise potentials, global interactions in the system also exist, but they occur only through pairwise terms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In many-body potentials, the potential energy cannot be found by a sum over pairs of atoms, as these interactions are calculated explicitly as a combination of higher-order terms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In the statistical view, the dependency between the variables cannot in general be expressed using only pairwise products of the degrees of freedom.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For example, the Tersoff potential, which was originally used to simulate carbon, silicon, and germanium, and has since been used for a wide range of other materials, involves a sum over groups of three atoms, with the angles between the atoms being an important factor in the potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Semi-empirical potentials make use of the matrix representation from quantum mechanics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] However, the values of the matrix elements are found through empirical formulae that estimate the degree of overlap of specific atomic orbitals.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The matrix is then diagonalized to determine the occupancy of the different atomic orbitals, and empirical formulae are used once again to determine the energy contributions of the orbitals.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] There are a wide variety of semi-empirical potentials, termed tight-binding potentials, which vary according to the atoms being modeled.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Most classical force fields implicitly include the effect of polarizability, e.g., by scaling up the partial charges obtained from quantum chemical calculations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] These partial charges are stationary with respect to the mass of the atom.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] But molecular dynamics simulations can explicitly model polarizability with the introduction of induced dipoles through different methods, such as Drude particles or fluctuating charges.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This allows for a dynamic redistribution of charge between atoms which responds to the local chemical environment.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For many years, polarizable MD simulations have been touted as the next generation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For homogenous liquids such as water, increased accuracy has been achieved through the inclusion of polarizability.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Some promising results have also been achieved for proteins.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] However, it is still uncertain how to best approximate polarizability in a simulation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The point becomes more important when a particle experiences different environments during its simulation trajectory, e.g. translocation of a drug through a cell membrane.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In classical molecular dynamics, one potential energy surface (usually the ground state) is represented in the force field.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This is a consequence of the Born–Oppenheimer approximation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In excited states, chemical reactions or when a more accurate representation is needed, electronic behavior can be obtained from first principles using a quantum mechanical method, such as density functional theory.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This is named *Ab Initio Molecular Dynamics* (AIMD).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Due to the cost of treating the electronic degrees of freedom, the computational burden of these simulations is far higher than classical molecular dynamics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For this reason, AIMD is typically limited to smaller systems and shorter times.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] QM (quantum-mechanical) methods are very powerful.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A new class of method has emerged that combines the good points of QM (accuracy) and MM (speed) calculations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] These methods are termed mixed or hybrid quantum-mechanical and molecular mechanics methods (hybrid QM/MM).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The most important advantage of hybrid QM/MM method is the speed.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The cost of doing classical molecular dynamics (MM) in the most straightforward case scales O(n2), where n is the number of atoms in the system.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This is mainly due to electrostatic interactions term (every particle interacts with every other particle).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] However, use of cutoff radius, periodic pair-list updates and more recently the variations of the particle-mesh Ewald's (PME) method has reduced this to between O(n) to O(n2).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In other words, if a system with twice as many atoms is simulated then it would take between two and four times as much computing power.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] On the other hand, the simplest *ab initio* calculations typically scale O(n3) or worse (restricted Hartree–Fock calculations have been suggested to scale ~O(n2.7)).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] To overcome the limit, a small part of the system is treated quantum-mechanically (typically active-site of an enzyme) and the remaining system is treated classically.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In more sophisticated implementations, QM/MM methods exist to treat both light nuclei susceptible to quantum effects (such as hydrogens) and electronic states.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This allows generating hydrogen wave-functions (similar to electronic wave-functions).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This methodology has been useful in investigating phenomena such as hydrogen tunneling.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] One example where QM/MM methods have provided new discoveries is the calculation of hydride transfer in the enzyme liver alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In this case, quantum tunneling is important for the hydrogen, as it determines the reaction rate.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] At the other end of the detail scale are coarse-grained and lattice models.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Instead of explicitly representing every atom of the system, one uses "pseudo-atoms" to represent groups of atoms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] MD simulations on very large systems may require such large computer resources that they cannot easily be studied by traditional all-atom methods.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Similarly, simulations of processes on long timescales (beyond about 1 microsecond) are prohibitively expensive, because they require so many time steps.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In these cases, one can sometimes tackle the problem by using reduced representations, which are also called coarse-grained models.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Examples for coarse graining (CG) methods are discontinuous molecular dynamics (CG-DMD) and Go-models.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Coarse-graining is done sometimes taking larger pseudo-atoms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Such united atom approximations have been used in MD simulations of biological membranes.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Implementation of such approach on systems where electrical properties are of interest can be challenging owing to the difficulty of using a proper charge distribution on the pseudo-atoms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The aliphatic tails of lipids are represented by a few pseudo-atoms by gathering 2 to 4 methylene groups into each pseudo-atom.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The parameterization of these very coarse-grained models must be done empirically, by matching the behavior of the model to appropriate experimental data or all-atom simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Ideally, these parameters should account for both enthalpic and entropic contributions to free energy in an implicit way.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] When coarse-graining is done at higher levels, the accuracy of the dynamic description may be less reliable.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] But very coarse-grained models have been used successfully to examine a wide range of questions in structural biology, liquid crystal organization, and polymer glasses.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The simplest form of coarse-graining is the *united atom* (sometimes called *extended atom*) and was used in most early MD simulations of proteins, lipids, and nucleic acids.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] For example, instead of treating all four atoms of a CH3 methyl group explicitly (or all three atoms of CH2 methylene group), one represents the whole group with one pseudo-atom.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] It must, of course, be properly parameterized so that its van der Waals interactions with other groups have the proper distance-dependence.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Similar considerations apply to the bonds, angles, and torsions in which the pseudo-atom participates.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In this kind of united atom representation, one typically eliminates all explicit hydrogen atoms except those that have the capability to participate in hydrogen bonds (*polar hydrogens*).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] An example of this is the CHARMM 19 force-field.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The polar hydrogens are usually retained in the model, because proper treatment of hydrogen bonds requires a reasonably accurate description of the directionality and the electrostatic interactions between the donor and acceptor groups.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A hydroxyl group, for example, can be both a hydrogen bond donor, and a hydrogen bond acceptor, and it would be impossible to treat this with one OH pseudo-atom.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] About half the atoms in a protein or nucleic acid are non-polar hydrogens, so the use of united atoms can provide a substantial savings in computer time.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Machine Learning Force Fields (MLFFs) represent one approach to modeling interatomic interactions in molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] MLFFs can achieve accuracy close to that of ab initio methods.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Once trained, MLFFs are much faster than direct quantum mechanical calculations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] MLFFs address the limitations of traditional force fields by learning complex potential energy surfaces directly from high-level quantum mechanical data.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Several software packages now support MLFFs, including VASP and open-source libraries like DeePMD-kit and SchNetPack.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] MLIPs have been widely applied in molecular dynamics simulations and materials science, enabling the study of complex phenomena such as defect formation, phase transformations, and chemical reactions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In many simulations of a solute-solvent system the main focus is on the behavior of the solute with little interest of the solvent behavior particularly in those solvent molecules residing in regions far from the solute molecule.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Solvents may influence the dynamic behavior of solutes via random collisions and by imposing a frictional drag on the motion of the solute through the solvent.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The use of non-rectangular periodic boundary conditions, stochastic boundaries and solvent shells can all help reduce the number of solvent molecules required and enable a larger proportion of the computing time to be spent instead on simulating the solute.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] It is also possible to incorporate the effects of a solvent without needing any explicit solvent molecules present.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] One example of this approach is to use a potential mean force (PMF) which describes how the free energy changes as a particular coordinate is varied.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The free energy change described by PMF contains the averaged effects of the solvent.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A long range interaction is an interaction in which the spatial interaction falls off no faster than $r^{-d}$ where d is the dimensionality of the system.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Examples include charge-charge interactions between ions and dipole-dipole interactions between molecules.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Modelling these forces presents quite a challenge as they are significant over a distance which may be larger than half the box length with simulations of many thousands of particles.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Though one solution would be to significantly increase the size of the box length, this brute force approach is less than ideal as the simulation would become computationally very expensive.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Spherically truncating the potential is also out of the question as unrealistic behaviour may be observed when the distance is close to the cut off distance.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The most important long-range interactions are electrostatic interactions between two (partly) charge atoms.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] At present, the most used method is Particle Mesh Ewald (PME).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] PME uses Ewald summations to split the calculations into a short- and long range part.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The short-range part calculates all interactions within a cut-off range, the long-range part is solved in reciprocal space, using fast Fourier transforms (FFTs).
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The high accuracy and high calculation speed made PME the gold standard for many years.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] However the increase use of parallelization, PME runs into a communication bottleneck because the FFTs require an all-to-all communication.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A attractive PME alternative are the fast multipole methods (FMM), which are not affected by an increase in parallelization.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Additionally, FMM allows simulations of much larger systems and removes the necessity of periodic boundary conditions, particularly useful for gas-phase simulations of bio-molecules.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Steered molecular dynamics (SMD) simulations, or force probe simulations, apply forces to a protein in order to manipulate its structure by pulling it along desired degrees of freedom.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] These experiments can be used to reveal structural changes in a protein at the atomic level.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] SMD is often used to simulate events such as mechanical unfolding or stretching.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] There are two typical protocols of SMD: one in which pulling velocity is held constant, and one in which applied force is constant.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Typically, part of the studied system (e.g., an atom in a protein) is restrained by a harmonic potential.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Forces are then applied to specific atoms at either a constant velocity or a constant force.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Umbrella sampling is used to move the system along the desired reaction coordinate by varying, for example, the forces, distances, and angles manipulated in the simulation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Through umbrella sampling, all of the system's configurations—both high-energy and low-energy—are adequately sampled.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Then, each configuration's change in free energy can be calculated as the potential of mean force.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A popular method of computing PMF is through the weighted histogram analysis method (WHAM), which analyzes a series of umbrella sampling simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] A lot of important applications of SMD are in the field of drug discovery and biomolecular sciences.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] SMD was used to investigate the stability of Alzheimer's protofibrils, to study the protein ligand interaction in cyclin-dependent kinase 5 and even to show the effect of electric field on thrombin (protein) and aptamer (nucleotide) complex among many other interesting studies.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Molecular dynamics is used in many fields of science.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Another important application of MD method benefits from its ability of 3-dimensional characterization and analysis of microstructural evolution at atomic scale.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Molecular dynamics (MD) simulations have also been increasingly applied in cement and concrete research to investigate the nanoscale mechanical behavior and structural characteristics of hydration products.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In particular, MD has been used to estimate the elastic properties of major clinker phases (C3S, C2S, C3A, and C4AF) and to evaluate the performance of different force fields in predicting their bulk, shear, and Young's moduli.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Further studies have focused on calcium silicate hydrate (C–S–H) gel, which constitutes approximately 50–70% of hydrated cement paste.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Using MD and Monte Carlo simulations, the influence of water content, Ca/Si ratio, and structural defects on the mechanical properties and stiffness of C–S–H have been explored in detail, revealing that increasing water content or Ca/Si ratio generally decreases the Young's modulus of the gel.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Such nanoscale insights contribute to multiscale modeling frameworks that link atomic-scale properties of cement hydrates to the macroscopic performance of concrete, enabling the design of low-clinker, high-performance, and more sustainable cementitious materials.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Molecular modeling on GPU is the technique of using a graphics processing unit (GPU) for molecular simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] In 2007, Nvidia introduced video cards that could be used not only to show graphics but also for scientific calculations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] These cards include many arithmetic units (as of 2022, up to 18,176 in the RTX 6000 Ada) working in parallel.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] Long before this event, the computational power of video cards was purely used to accelerate graphics calculations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] The new features of these cards made it possible to develop parallel programs in a high-level application programming interface (API) named CUDA.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] This technology substantially simplified programming by enabling programs to be written in C/C++.
[src:molecular-dynamics/molecular-dynamics] More recently, OpenCL allows cross-platform GPU acceleration.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] The **Nosé–Hoover thermostat** is a deterministic algorithm for constant-temperature molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] It was originally developed by Shuichi Nosé and was improved further by William G.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] Although the heat bath of Nosé–Hoover thermostat consists of only one imaginary particle, simulation systems achieve realistic constant-temperature condition (canonical ensemble).
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] Therefore, the Nosé–Hoover thermostat has been commonly used as one of the most accurate and efficient methods for constant-temperature molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] In classical molecular dynamics, simulations are done in the microcanonical ensemble; a number of particles, volume, and energy have a constant value.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] In experiments, however, the temperature is generally controlled instead of the energy.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] The ensemble of this experimental condition is called a canonical ensemble.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] Importantly, the canonical ensemble is different from microcanonical ensemble from the viewpoint of statistical mechanics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] Several methods have been introduced to keep the temperature constant while using the microcanonical ensemble.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] Popular techniques to control temperature include velocity rescaling, the Andersen thermostat, the Nosé–Hoover thermostat, Nosé–Hoover chains, the Berendsen thermostat and Langevin dynamics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] The central idea is to simulate in such a way that we obtain a canonical ensemble, where we fix the particle number N , the volume V and the temperature T .
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] This means that these three quantities are fixed and do not fluctuate.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] Although the temperature and the average kinetic energy are fixed, the instantaneous kinetic energy fluctuates (and with it the velocities of the particles).
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] where *g* is the number of independent momentum degrees of freedom of the system, *R* and *P* represent all coordinates $\mathbf {r_{i}}$ and $\mathbf {p_{i}}$ and *Q* is a parameter which determines the timescale on which the rescaling occurs.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] Improper choice of *Q* can lead to ineffective thermostatting or the introduction of nonphysical temperature oscillations.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] The coordinates *R*, *P* and *t* in this Hamiltonian are virtual.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] where the coordinates with an accent are the real coordinates.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] The ensemble average of the above Hamiltonian at $g=3N$ is equal to the canonical ensemble average.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] Hoover (1985) used the phase-space continuity equation, a generalized Liouville equation, to establish what is now known as the Nosé–Hoover thermostat.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] This approach does not require the scaling of the time (or, in effect, of the momentum) by *s*.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] The Nosé–Hoover algorithm is nonergodic for a single harmonic oscillator.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] In simple terms, it means that the algorithm fails to generate a canonical distribution for a single harmonic oscillator.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] This feature of the Nosé–Hoover algorithm has prompted the development of newer thermostatting algorithms—the kinetic moments method that controls the first two moments of the kinetic energy, Bauer–Bulgac–Kusnezov scheme, Nosé–Hoover chains, etc.
[src:molecular-dynamics/nosé-hoover-thermostat] Using a similar method, other techniques like the Braga–Travis configurational thermostat and the Patra–Bhattacharya full phase thermostat have been proposed.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In molecular dynamics simulations and Monte Carlo molecular modeling, PBCs are usually applied to calculate properties of bulk gases, liquids, crystals, or mixtures.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] A common application uses PBC to simulate solvated macromolecules in a bath of explicit solvent.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Born–von Karman boundary conditions are periodic boundary conditions for a special system.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In electromagnetics, PBC can be applied for different mesh types to analyze the electromagnetic properties of periodical structures.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Three-dimensional PBCs are useful for approximating the behavior of macro-scale systems of gases, liquids, and solids.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Three-dimensional PBCs can also be used to simulate planar surfaces, in which case two-dimensional PBCs are often more suitable.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Two-dimensional PBCs for planar surfaces are also called *slab boundary conditions*; in this case, PBCs are used for two Cartesian coordinates (e.g., x and y), and the third coordinate (z) extends to infinity.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] PBCs can be used in conjunction with Ewald summation methods (e.g., the particle mesh Ewald method) to calculate electrostatic forces in the system.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] But PBCs also introduce correlational artifacts that do not respect the translational invariance of the system, requiring constraints on the composition and size of the simulation box.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In simulations of solid systems, the strain field arising from any inhomogeneity in the system will be artificially truncated and modified by the periodic boundary.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Similarly, the wavelength of sound or shock waves and phonons in the system is limited by the box size.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In simulations containing ionic (Coulomb) interactions, the net electrostatic charge of the system must be zero to avoid summing to an infinite charge when PBCs are applied.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In some applications it is appropriate to obtain neutrality by adding ions such as sodium or chloride (as counterions) in appropriate numbers if the molecules of interest are charged.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Sometimes ions are even added to a system in which the molecules of interest are neutral, to approximate the ionic strength of the solution in which the molecules naturally appear.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Maintenance of the minimum-image convention also generally requires that a spherical cutoff radius for nonbonded forces be at most half the length of one side of a cubic box.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Even in electrostatically neutral systems, a net dipole moment of the unit cell can introduce a spurious bulk-surface energy, equivalent to pyroelectricity in polar crystals.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Another consequence of applying PBCs to a simulated system such as a liquid or a solid is that this hypothetical system has no contact with its "surroundings", due to it being infinite in all directions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Therefore, long-range energy contributions such as the electrostatic potential, and by extension the energies of charged particles like electrons, are not automatically aligned to experimental energy scales.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Mathematically, this energy level ambiguity corresponds to the sum of the electrostatic energy being dependent on a surface term that needs to be set by the user of the method.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] The size of the simulation box must also be large enough to prevent periodic artifacts from occurring due to the unphysical topology of the simulation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In a box that is too small, a macromolecule may interact with its own image in a neighboring box, which is functionally equivalent to a molecule's "head" interacting with its own "tail".
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] This produces highly unphysical dynamics in most macromolecules, although the magnitude of the consequences and thus the appropriate box size relative to the size of the macromolecules depends on the intended length of the simulation, the desired accuracy, and the anticipated dynamics.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] For example, simulations of protein folding that begin from the native state may undergo smaller fluctuations, and therefore may not require as large a box, as simulations that begin from a random coil conformation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] However, the effects of solvation shells on the observed dynamics – in simulation or in experiment – are not well understood.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] A common recommendation based on simulations of DNA is to require at least 1 nm of solvent around the molecules of interest in every dimension.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] An object which has passed through one face of the simulation box should re-enter through the opposite face—or its image should do it.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Evidently, a strategic decision must be made: Do we (A) "fold back" particles into the simulation box when they leave it, or do we (B) let them go on (but compute interactions with the nearest images)?
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] The decision has no effect on the course of the simulation, but if the user is interested in mean displacements, diffusion lengths, etc., the second option is preferable.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] To implement a PBC algorithm, at least two steps are needed.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Distance and vector between objects should obey the minimum image criterion.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] For three-dimensional PBCs, both operations should be repeated in all 3 dimensions.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] These operations can be written in a much more compact form for orthorhombic cells if the origin is shifted to a corner of the box.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] The fastest way of carrying out this operation depends on the processor architecture.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] was found to be fastest on x86-64 processors in 2013.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] For non-orthorhombic cells the situation is more complicated.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In simulations of ionic systems more complicated operations may be needed to handle the long-range Coulomb interactions spanning several box images, for instance Ewald summation.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] PBC requires the unit cell to be a shape that will tile perfectly into a three-dimensional crystal.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Thus, a spherical or elliptical droplet cannot be used.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] A cube or rectangular prism is the most intuitive and common choice, but can be computationally expensive due to unnecessary amounts of solvent molecules in the corners, distant from the central macromolecules.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] A common alternative that requires less volume is the truncated octahedron.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] For simulations in 2D and 3D space, cubic periodic boundary condition is most commonly used since it is simplest in coding.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In computer simulation of high dimensional systems, however, the hypercubic periodic boundary condition can be less efficient because corners occupy most part of the space.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In general dimension, unit cell can be viewed as the Wigner-Seitz cell of certain lattice packing.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] For example, the hypercubic periodic boundary condition corresponds to the hypercubic lattice packing.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] It is then preferred to choose a unit cell which corresponds to the dense packing of that dimension.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] In 4D this is D4 lattice; and E8 lattice in 8-dimension.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] The implementation of these high dimensional periodic boundary conditions is equivalent to error correction code approaches in information theory.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Under periodic boundary conditions, the linear momentum of a system is conserved, but angular momentum is not.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] The conventional explanation of this is based on Noether's theorem, which says that conservation of angular momentum follows from rotational invariance of Lagrangian.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] But this approach has been shown to be inconsistent: it fails to explain the absence of conservation of angular momentum of a single particle moving in a periodic cell.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] Lagrangian of the particle is constant and therefore rotationally invariant, but its angular momentum is not conserved.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] This is because Noether's theorem is usually formulated for closed systems.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] The periodic cell exchanges mass momentum, angular momentum, and energy with the neighboring cells.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] These additional conserved quantities introduce minor artifacts related to the statistical mechanical definition of temperature, the departure of the velocity distributions from a Boltzmann distribution, and violations of equipartition for systems containing particles with heterogeneous masses.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] The simplest of these effects is that a system of *N* particles will behave, in the molecular dynamics ensemble, as a system of *N-1* particles.
[src:molecular-dynamics/periodic-boundary-conditions] These artifacts have quantifiable consequences for small toy systems containing only perfectly hard particles; they have not been studied in depth for standard biomolecular simulations, but given the size of such systems, the effects will be largely negligible.
